subSection.paragraph:
Phytoplankton is estimated to be responsible for roughly 50% of global primary production and forms the basis of the marine food web (
Field et al., 1998
). Algal cells forming the phytoplankton experience environmental fluctuations in their habitat during sinking or transport by currents. Shifts in nutrient availability, light, and temperature (
Vidal et al., 2017
) can lead to a change in the species composition of the phytoplanktonic community. However, these factors also influence the physiology of the persisting cells. In the long term, global warming alters the productivity and composition of phytoplankton (
Thomas et al., 2012
). Additional parameters connected to temperature, like dissolved CO 
2
and salinity, influence the algae as well (
Sugie et al., 2020
). Surface salinity patterns, mainly influenced by increasing evaporation and precipitation or other freshwater influx, are becoming more important on a global level due to climate change (
Durack and Wijffels, 2010
; 
Zika et al., 2018
). Because algae are surface-dwelling primary producers, they are directly affected by such changes in ocean salinity. Considering the importance of phytoplankton for global primary production, it is vital that we understand the effect of alterations in salinity concerning growth, community composition, and metabolism.

A change in salinity in the aqueous environment of a phytoplankton cell subjects it to osmotic stress. This can be alleviated by water flux in or out of the cell or adjustment of the intracellular salt concentration. These salts include inorganic ions and organic compatible solutes, called osmolytes (
Kirst, 1989
). The accumulation of osmolytes is believed to be the most widespread and long-term successful mechanism of osmoadaptation to increased salinity in free-living algae (
Ochsenkühn et al., 2017
).

The main body of literature about the identity and quantity of organic osmolytes in microalgae stems from targeted analytics (
Hellebust, 1976
; 
Dickson and Kirst, 1987
). Modern untargeted screening using high-resolution mass spectrometry can offer additional insight (
Thume et al., 2018
) and reveal previously unrecognized metabolic connections. The opportunity to unravel novel aspects in algal physiology prompted us to perform a salt-stress experiment on diatoms and analyze extracts with liquid- and gas-chromatography coupled to high-resolution mass spectrometry in an untargeted manner. This revealed metabolites and pathways responding to salinity changes and allowed us to document metabolic networks connected to osmoadaptation.

To best mimic natural non-limiting conditions and at the same time obtain a high number of cells for extraction, salinity stress experiments were performed with algal cultures in the later logarithmic growth phase. Relatively high salt concentration for the stress (initially 60 PSU) was selected so that it could induce significant changes in the algal endometabolome. We adjusted salinity stress so that it does not lead to algal cell death since otherwise changes in the endometabolome would be associated with cell death processes. The elevation of medium salinity to values close to 60 PSU was previously performed to investigate the effect of increased salinity on the growth, and metabolome of diatoms (
Bergeijk et al., 2003
; 
Rijstenbil, 2003
; 
García et al., 2012
; 
Jaramillo-Madrid et al., 2020
).

In this study, analysis of the stress response was performed at two time points after salinity increase. A short-term salinity stress response was analyzed 24 h after the stress, which is on average less than doubling time of diatoms (
Laws, 2013
). Thus, direct response of the cells was analyzed. The long-term response was examined 96 h after the increase in salt content when algal cells could divide at least two times. Consequently, salinity stress adaptation of the next generations could be examined.

Among the identified metabolites detected with GC-MS, pipecolinic acid and proline exhibited the highest increase in concentration. In total, up-regulation of 11 amino acids was observed. Also, increase in content of 8 sugars (one disaccharide, five monosaccharides, and two inositols) was detected (
Table S1
).

In response to the long-term salinity stress, statistically significant dysregulation was shown for 85 compounds detected with GC-MS. Six of them were down-regulated, and the content of 79 was increased (cell count normalized data) (Fig. S7). Among identified metabolites, only citric acid showed a decrease in content, while contents of others were increased. Similar to the short-term salinity stress response, the most upregulated identified compounds were amino acids and amines, including proline and pipecolinic acid. Their fold changes increased compared to the values at the 24 h time point. Also increase of pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid and threonine was observed (
Table S1
).

Salinity is almost constant in the open oceans and varies only little between 33 and 37 PSU. In nearshore waters, however, salinity fluctuations are substantial. Future climate change scenarios predict increased changes in water salinity due to evaporation or reduced freshwater intake from rivers due to low precipitation (
Glaser and Karsten, 2020
).

Diatoms can tolerate much higher salinity changes than the salinity ranges of their original habitat (
Yamamoto et al., 2017
). It was, however, observed that an increase in salinity negatively correlates with growth rates and affects the chemical composition of diatoms (
Bergeijk et al., 2003
; 
Rijstenbil 2003
; 
García et al., 2012
; 
Jaramillo-Madrid et al., 2020
). We opted to evaluate the physiological and metabolic response of three model diatoms to extreme salinity stress. We initially tested their tolerance to hypersalinity to avoid stress resulting in culture death. After salinity increase to 60 PSU 

P. tricornutum

and 

T. pseudonana

responded with a strongly reduced growth compared to the control. Both algae continued to divide and the chlorophyll content of the culture increased under control and salinity stress conditions (
Fig. S1-S
2
). This confirms previous findings of salt tolerance for these two algae (
Jaramillo-Madrid et al., 2020
). 

S. marinoi

was not as tolerant towards increased salinity regimes and did not grow at a salinity over 50 PSU (
Fig. S3-S
4
). This is in accordance with a survey of Branda, who determined growth of this alga at 5 to 45 PSU (
Branda, 1984
).

The most widespread adaptation mechanism of diatoms to osmotic changes in their environment is the adjustment of the cellular concentration of compatible solutes (
Ochsenkühn et al., 2017
). Many studies address the regulation of such metabolites mainly based on the targeted analysis of candidate compounds. Amino acids and their metabolites are common up-regulated compounds upon hypersalinity stress. Also, organic sulfur compounds, including the dominant dimethylsulfoniopropionate (DMSP), have been quantitatively surveyed (
Dickson and Kirst, 1987
; 
Gebser and Pohnert, 2013
). We set out here to determine the metabolome changes of three model diatoms with an untargeted approach. This allows the identification of common and unique compatible solutes in the diatoms and linking the dysregulated metabolites to metabolic pathways. We used an analytical approach based on high-resolution mass spectrometry. By combining GC-MS and LC-MS analysis, we could reach an unprecedentedly broad metabolic coverage of up to 344 features with GC-MS and 548 features with LC-MS.

