Leimer et al., 1977
).

subSection.paragraph:
Amino acids play an important role as compatible solutes. Accordingly, they comprise the most significant group among the identified dysregulated compounds in response to hyperosmotic stress (
Table 1
). Their accumulation was explained with continuing 
de novo
amino acid biosynthesis and due to reduced protein synthesis (
Hellebust, 1976
; 
García et al., 2012
). Alternatively, the high content of amino acids in response to osmotic stress could be caused by protein degradation, as shown for higher plants (
Fukutoku and Yamada, 1981
; 
Joshi et al., 2010
).

Accumulation of 4-hydroxyproline and pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid was detected for all studied diatoms. These two metabolites are biosynthetically derived from proline. Accumulation of 4-hydroxyproline in response to salinity stress and its osmolytic function was reported in bacteria (
Mimura et al., 1994
; 
Kim et al., 2017
). Increase in pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid upon salt and drought stress has also been found in higher plants (
Kissoudis et al., 2015
; 
Zhang et al., 2017
). The role as an osmoprotectant in other species points towards a similar role in diatoms.

Quaternary ammonium compounds are another major class of osmolytes (
Yancey, 2005
). For the algae investigated, quaternary ammonium compounds, such as glycine betaine, proline betaine (stachydrine), and acylcarnitines could be identified among the significantly increased metabolites upon salinity stress.

Interestingly, dimethylsulfoniopropionate, a metabolite often discussed as diatom compatible solute was not among those compounds that were up-regulated according to our criteria. The metabolite was detected in all investigated diatoms but significant up-regulation could not be confirmed. This is in accordance with observations that more subtle osmoadaptations go ahead with the regulation of amino acids and quartery ammounium metabolites, while DMSP, that is highly abundant, only compensates salinity changes under extreme stress conditions (
Gebser and Pohnert, 2013
).

This work addresses the orchestrated metabolic response of diatom metabolism in response to hypersalinity. We can distinguish between universally up-regulated metabolites in all three diatoms under hypersalinity stress that support a common adaptation mechanism. Amino acids, saccharides and inositols were most conserved (
Liu and Hellebust, 1976
; 
Scholz and Liebezeit, 2012
). The majority of regulated metabolites was specific to one or two species. The common repertoire of regulated metabolites is thus accompanied by species-specific physiological responses.

The untargeted screening introduced here allowed not only the detection of previously identified candidates. It led to the identification of several metabolites that were previously not associated with salinity stress response in diatoms, e.g. 4-hydroxyproline, pipecolinic acid, myoinositol, threonic acid, and acylcarnitines. For some of these metabolites their osmoprotectant role was described in plants or bacteria (
Mimura et al., 1994
; 
Kets and Bont, 1997
; 
Moulin et al., 2000
; 
Neshich et al., 2013
; 
Kim et al., 2017
). Up-regulation of these metabolites was detected in at least for two of three studied diatoms.

For endometabolome extraction, LC-, GC-MS sample, and analytical standard preparation (if not stated otherwise), the following reagents were used: methanol (SupraSolv, Merck, 
Germany
), ethanol (LiChrosolv, Supelco, Merck, 
Germany
), chloroform (HPLC grade, Fisher Scientific, 
UK
), acetonitrile (CHEMSOLUTE, Th. Geyer, 
Germany
), water (Chromasolv Plus for HPLC, Honeywell, 
Germany
).

Cell counting was conducted using a Fuchs Rosenthal Counting Chamber (Glaswarenfabrik Karl Hecht, 
Germany
) under the light microscope Leica DM 2000 (Leica Microsystems, Wetzlar, 
Germany
).

GC-MS data pre-processing was performed as described in 
Stettin et al. (2020)
. Briefly, raw files were converted into. mzXML format using Proteowizard Suite (proteowizard.sourceforge.net) with vendor peak picking enabled. Data were pre-processed with an R script (
Stettin et al., 2020
), which includes the XCMS package (
Smith et al., 2006
), CAMERA package (
Kuhl et al., 2012
), and MetaMS package (
Wehrens et al., 2014
). Obtained data was processed further with StatTarget package (
Luan et al., 2018
) for quality control based signal drift correction. All settings were used as published except minimum fragments for features grouping was set to 5 (
Stettin et al., 2020
).

(
Hulsen et al., 2008
).

Identification of metabolites detected with GC-MS analysis was conducted using the NIST 2011 Mass Spectral Library database (National Institute of Standards and Technology, 
USA
), MetFrag (
Ruttkies et al., 2016
) and MS-Finder platforms (
Tsugawa et al., 2016
). Results were manually checked for processing artifacts.

Identification of unknowns detected with LC-MS analysis was performed using Sirius version 4.4.29 (
Dührkop et al., 2019
). Depending on the tree fragmentation score (
B¨ocker and Dührkop, 2016
), and the percentage of CSI:FingerID tool (
Dührkop et al., 2015
) putative identification of unknowns was performed.
